Phasmida , or Phasmatodea are a small Order of phytophagous insects, famous for their wonderful camouflage as part of plants such as twigs and even leaves (
). Some of these species have both forewings and hindwings, but are unable to fly (
,
). Wing function and evolution in the Phasmida have been studied in some detail (
,
,
,
). Some of these short-winged (micropterous) species use scare displays as their main derived function of non-flight wings (
,
). The bodies of these micro-winged startle-display species are cryptically colored but may have brightly aposematic coloration in the anal area. Such examples are seen in the small red-wing stick insect genus
Oxyartes
as an example ( Fig. 1 ).

